    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-07-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-07-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="10"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d10">
                <head>10. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_BZK_1">Brzezinski</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d10fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Country File, Box 4, Angola:
                        1/77–12/78. Secret. <persName corresp="#p_BZK_1">Brzezinski</persName> wrote
                        in the upper right-hand corner: “DA please <hi rend="italic">act</hi> on
                        this in <gloss target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss>-working group. ZB.” <persName
                            corresp="#p_DC_1">Dodson</persName> wrote below this: “(C[op]y sent to
                        Henze 7/14)”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-07-12">July 12, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Cubans in Angola</item>
                </list>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_USIA_1">USIA</gloss> has begun to move on publicizing the
                    growing disillusionment with Cubans in Angola. <persName corresp="#p_RJE_1">John
                        Reinhardt</persName> has informed me that <gloss target="#t_VOA_1"
                        >VOA</gloss> has made a careful check of materials available in the public
                    domain indicating awareness of and dissatisfaction with Soviet and Cuban
                    interference in African affairs. Attached is a copy of a recent <gloss
                        target="#t_VOA_1">VOA</gloss> news analysis dealing with Socialist
                    imperialism in Africa.<note n="2" xml:id="d10fn2">Not found attached. The July
                        11 <gloss target="#t_VOA_1">VOA</gloss> news analysis entitled “Africa and
                        the ‘New Socialist Imperialism’” is in the National Security Council,
                            <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> Administration
                        Intelligence Files, Subject Files A–E, Box 25, Angola 11 July 1977–18 April
                        1978.</note> This analysis will be used in English, French, Portuguese, and
                    Swahili broadcasts to Africa.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_VOA_1">VOA</gloss> will continue to pursue this matter.<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d10fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote below this paragraph:
                        “OK—Let’s push actual effort—not just analysis—Also radio broadcasts to
                        Cuba—Keep me informed. J.”</note>
                </p>
            </div>
